<h2>Who Uses the Glow Protocol</h2>

<p>The typical user falls into one of several categories. Adults over 40 noticing visible skin aging (fine lines, loss of firmness, dull complexion) who want a more targeted approach than topical skincare alone. Athletes or active individuals who want recovery support alongside skin benefits. People with scarring from acne, surgery, or injury who want to support tissue remodeling. And those interested in comprehensive anti-aging who want one protocol addressing multiple aspects of age-related tissue decline.</p>

<h2>Comparison to Standard Skincare</h2>

<p>Topical skincare (retinoids, vitamin C, hyaluronic acid, sunscreen) addresses the skin from the outside in. The Glow Protocol addresses it from the inside out. These approaches are complementary, not competing.</p>

<p>Retinoids increase cell turnover at the skin surface. GHK-Cu increases collagen synthesis in the deeper dermal layers. Vitamin C provides antioxidant protection topically. BPC-157 and TB-500 reduce systemic inflammation and promote repair internally. The best results come from combining good topical skincare with the Glow Protocol's systemic support.</p>

<p>The Glow Protocol costs more and requires injections, making it a more committed intervention than applying serums. It's not a replacement for basic skincare (sunscreen, moisturizer, retinoid). It's a next-level addition for people who've optimized the basics and want further improvement from the biological level up.</p>

<h2>Safety and Practical Notes</h2>

<p>All three peptides in the Glow Protocol have clean safety profiles in animal studies and extensive user reporting. The main side effects are injection site irritation, mild fatigue during TB-500 loading phase, and occasional headache. The angiogenesis concern (relevant to BPC-157 and TB-500) applies: anyone with active cancer should avoid this protocol.</p>

<p>For the topical GHK-Cu component, start with every other day application for the first week to test skin sensitivity, then increase to daily. Minor irritation in the first few days is possible, especially in combination with retinoids. If using both, apply retinoid in the evening and GHK-Cu in the morning.</p>

<p>The Glow Protocol represents one of the more evidence-based peptide stacks for anti-aging because each component has independent research supporting its mechanism. The combination hasn't been studied as a unit, but the complementary pathways make the rationale for stacking straightforward.</p>
